  When I got the PC-GPE I started to look it and discovered that you
can learn from it how to read a PCX file. I was glad!!! My first real
file format. It was not difficult and so I did a Viewer. You have it here
(PCXView). There is also a CELViewer (works only on MCGA). You can put them

  In this ZIP file there are 5 files all in pascal (.PAS):

    CEL2PCX.PAS: converts between a CEL file and a PCX.
    PCX2CEL.PAS: converts between a PCX file and a CEL.
    IMAGES.PAS : A unit that contains procedures to load
                 PCX, CEL and some palette functions as well.
    PCXVIEW    : A command line PCX Viewer, works on files bigger then
                 320x200 too.
    CELVIEW    : A command line CEL Viewer, loads only the AA.EXE CEL's
                 not the AA-PRO (ANI.EXE).


  The CELView and PCXView programms are very usefull if you use the
Norton-Commander: just add them to the extention menu and then when
you press enter on a PCX you can view it. It is good because NC's viewer
does not supprot CEL's and using this you can easly view them. I my self
am using the DOS Navigator wich is a Turbo-Vision verion of NC. it works
better thefile support is faster, and eats less memory. But it does not
support pictures viewing. That's why I wrote those programs at the first
time.

  The PCXView also has something called SuperZoom: it is a smooth scrolling
in XMode (it is smooth in ewvery computer) and all the pictures are viewed
as 640x400. To zoom a picture press Z. To return press ESC.
  It is based on the zoom from Power-View. Thanks to Ariel Keselman for
helping me writing the Set_Chain4 procedures. And of course to ASPHIXIA's
tutors for introducing me to graphics and X-Mode for the first time.



